ive-url=https://archive.is/20120728003253/http://premiolaureldeoro.com/?p=112 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-28 |title=Carla Estrada y \u2018Amor Real\u2019 reciben \u2018Laurel de Oro\u2019 |language=Spanish |work=premiolaureldeoro.com |accessdate=2011-10-29 }}</ref>\n| Best Telenovela\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Television Actress\n| Adela Noriega\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Television Actor\n| Fernando Colunga\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| Ana Mart\u00edn\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| Mario Iv\u00e1n Mart\u00ednez\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Award for Artistic Trayectory\n| [[Helena Rojo]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Award for Artistic Trayectory\n| Mauricio Herrera\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| '''[[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma Metropolitana]]'''<ref name=\"estrada\"/>\n| Special Accolade \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"9\"| '''Golden Sun Awards'''{{#tag:ref|''Amor Real'' won 25 Sol de Oro Awards that are bestowed by the Mexico's National Association of Journalists. It won in all categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xenonpictures.com/AmorReal/flyer.pdf |title=The highly rated television run concludes March 4th |work=[[Xenon Pictures]] |accessdate=2011-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425121627/http://www.xenonpictures.com/AmorReal/flyer.pdf |archivedate=2012-04-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=277914 |title=Enamorados de Amor Real |language=Spanish |work=[[Univision|Univision.com]] |accessdate=2011-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050223022406/http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=277914 |archivedate=2005-02-23 }}</ref>|group=\"nb\"}}\n| Best Production\n| Carla Estrada\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Direction\n| M\u00f3nica Miguel\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Adaptation\n| Mar\u00eda Zarattini\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Leading Actress\n| Adela Noriega\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Leading Actor\n| Fernando Colunga\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Female Antagonist\n| [[Maya Mishalska]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Male Antagonist\n| Mauricio Islas\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best First Actress\n| Helena Rojo\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best First Actor\n| Mauricio Herrera\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| '''[[100 Mexicanos dijeron]]'''<ref name=\"estrada\"/>\n| VIP Award\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| '''Principios Award'''<ref name=\"estrada\"/>\n| Special Accolade \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2005\n| rowspan=\"2\"|'''[[Plaza de las Estrellas]]'''<ref name=\"estrada\"/>\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Luminaria de Oro \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|- \n| Carla Estrada\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| '''Festival Internacional<br> de Cine Las Garzas'''\n| Special Accolade\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n;Official sites \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060202100302/http://www.esmas.com/amorreal/ ''Amor real''] at [[esmas.com]] (in Spanish)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120408161456/http://www.xenonpictures.com/AmorReal/ ''Amor real''] at [[Xenon Pictures]]\n\n;Profiles \n* [http://www.terra.com/entretenimiento/tv/novelas/amor-real/ ''Amor real''] at [[Terra Networks|terra.com]] (in Spanish)\n* [http://novelasyseries.univision.com/amor-real ''Amor real''] at [[Univision|univision.com]] (in Spanish)\n* [http://www.alma-latina.net/AmorReal/AmorReal.shtml ''Amor real''] at Alma Latina\n* {{IMDb title|id=0341281|title=Amor real}}\n* [http://www.rtve.es/mediateca/fotos/20120716/mejores-imagenes-amor-real/97895.shtml Photo Gallery] at [[RTVE|rtve.es]]\n\n;Soundtrack\n* [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLdLfF1WqhwtcjscIvJH7KJjMlGzSlEeiA ''Amor Real''], incidental music\n\n;Articles\n* [http://novelasyseries.univision.com/amor-real-novela/lo-ultimo/article/2010-05-13/10-cosas-que-no-sabias 10 cosas que no sab\u00edas de Amor Real] at Univision.com (in Spanish)\n* [http://novelasyseries.univision.com/lo-ultimo/article/2010-03-12/torturas-de-antano-eran-las Torturas de anta\u00f1o eran las modas de Amor Real] at Univision.com (in Spanish)\n\n{{TVyNovelas Award for Best Telenovela |state=collapsed}}\n{{Televisa telenovelas 2000s}}\n{{Carla Estrada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amor Real}}\n[[Category:Amor real]]\n[[Category:2003 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2003 Mexican television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2003 Mexican television series endings]]\n[[Category:Mexican telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language telenovelas]]\n[[Category:Televisa telenovelas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican telenovela}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Amor real\n| image                    = Amor Real DVD.jpg\n| caption                  = DVD cover of ''Amor real''\n| genre                    = [[Telenovela]]\n| creator                  = Mar\u00eda Zarattini\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''Bodas de odio''|[[Caridad Bravo Adams]]}}\n| writer                   = V\u00edctor Manuel Medina\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Eric Morales\n* [[Monica Miguel]]\n}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|<!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n* [[Adela Noriega]]\n* [[Fernando Colunga]]\n* [[Mauricio Islas]]\n* [[Helena Rojo]]\n}}\n| music                    = [[Jorge Avenda\u00f1o]]\n| opentheme                = \"Amor real\" by [[Sin Bandera]]\n| country                  = Mexico\n| language                 = Spanish\n| num_seasons              = \n| num_episodes             = 95\n| executive_producer       = [[Carla Estrada]]\n| producer                 = Arturo Lorca\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* Jes\u00fas Acu\u00f1a\n* Alejandro Frutos\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Juan Franco\n* Luis Horacio Vald\u00e9s\n}}\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = <!-- Reliable source required -->\n| company                  = [[Televisa]]\n| network                  = [[Canal de las Estrellas]]\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] [[SDTV]]\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2003|6|9}} \n| last_aired               = {{End date|2003|10|17}} \n| preceded_by              = ''[[Las v\u00edas del amor]]''\n| followed_by              = ''[[Mariana de la noche]]''\n| related                  = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Lo que la vida me rob\u00f3]]''\n* ''[[Bodas de odio]]''\n}}\n| website                  = <!-- Remove or comment out this parameter line completely if URL exists on or is moved to Wikidata -->\n}}\n\n'''''Amor Real''''' (''Real Love''){{#tag:ref|Also dubbed as ''Real Love'' in English.|group=\"nb\"}} is a Mexican telenovela, which was produced and broadcast by [[Televisa]] in 2003. ''Amor Real'' is a historical [[telenovela]] set in the Mexican [[History of Mexico|post-independence]] period of the mid-19th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.invertia.com/noticias/articulo-final.asp?idNoticia=2732933&strGoo=amor-real-nueva-serie-romantica-sobremesa-estival&|title=\"Amor real\", la nueva serie rom\u00e1ntica de La 1 para la sobremesa estival|language=Spanish|publisher=invertia.com|date=2012-07-18|accessdate=2013-02-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045321/http://www.invertia.com/noticias/articulo-final.asp?idNoticia=2732933&strGoo=amor-real-nueva-serie-romantica-sobremesa-estival&|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"amorreal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20041018006256/en/Univision-Debuts-Amor-Real---Unforgettable-Love|title=Univision Debuts 'Amor Real' - an Unforgettable Love Story of Epic Proportions; Sweeping Tale Set in Turbulent 19th Century Mexico|publisher=Business Wire|date=October 19, 2004|accessdate =2013-02-02}}</ref> The telenovela aired on [[Univision]] in the United States, [[REN TV]] in Russia, and [[La 1 (Spain)|La 1]] in Spain, among others.  It was  successfully distributed to many countries worldwide.<ref name=\"amorreal\"/>  Also, in 2005, ''Amor real'' was released on DVD and it became the first telenovela to be released with English subtitles.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite web|last=Singer|first=Paola|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/0,,SB112467240069719249,00|title='Telenovelas' Become A Vibrant New Niche In the DVD Market|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=August 22, 2005|accessdate=June 16, 2013}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Televisa has released an abridged DVD version of the novela in several countries.<ref name=\"dvd\"/>\n\nThe [[List of Amor real characters|cast]] and the crew of the telenovela received many [[Amor Real#Awards and nominations|accolades]], including [[Premios TVyNovelas|TVyNovelas Award]] for [[TVyNovelas Award for Best Telenovela of the Year|Best Telenovela]], in 2004.\n\n== Overview ==\nIn the mid-19th century, in a time of [[Victorian morality]], challenging the rules of the [[aristocracy]] to which she belongs, Matilde Pe\u00f1alver y Berist\u00e1in, falls in love with Adolfo Sol\u00eds, an army soldier with no fortune; trusting that her father, Hilario - a fair and kind man - will let her marry him. But her mother, Augusta, is determined to force Matilde to marry a rich man in order to save the family from bankruptcy. Manuel Fuentes Guerra is the perfect candidate. He is an honorable and handsome young man who has just inherited a vast fortune. Augusta ignores the fact that Manuel is the illegitimate son of Joaqu\u00edn Fuentes Guerra, a powerful landlord who raped a native girl, and who only recognized Manuel as his heir on his deathbed.\n\nUsing all kinds of intrigues, the Augusta and her son Humberto send Adolfo to prison and convince Matilde to believe that he is married and has children. Overwhelmed and in despair, Matilde surrenders to her mother's pressure and agrees to marry Manuel, especially after she learns that he has paid the family's debts. Adolfo escapes from jail and immediately goes to look for his beloved Matilde, who has just married Manuel. Desperate, Adolfo manages to secretly speak with Matilde to clarify the misunderstandings. Swearing they will love each other forever, they decide to run away, but Manuel discovers them. Deeply hurt, Manuel is not willing to give her up. He forces her to leave with him, despite her love for Adolfo. After arriving at Manuel's [[hacienda]], Matilde has to put up with Antonia, the former administrator's daughter, who is in love with Manuel.\n\nMeanwhile, Adolfo, after an intense and frantic search finds Matilde and, intending to bring her back, poses as Manuel's new administrator. Manuel, unaware of Adolfo's real identity, sympathizes with him and gives him a special, friendly treatment. In spite of the situation, Adolfo has to admit that Manuel is a noble, fair man. At that point, Manuel and Matilde discover that they have been victims of Augusta and Humberto's deceit. As time goes by, the subtle attention and Manuel's avid desire end up conquering Matilde's heart. Suddenly one day, she realizes that the love she felt for Adolfo has disappeared and that she fell in love with Manuel. Matilde tells Adolfo the truth and urges him to leave. \n\nHeartbroken, Adolfo accepts his reality and leaves the ranch the same day Matilde announces to her husband that she's pregnant. The couple's happiness does not last long. Manuel discovers who his new administrator was and, in an instant, everything falls apart. Matilde's pleas and explanations cannot convince Manuel, he feels betrayed once again and cannot forgive her. Driven by anger, Manuel doubts his paternity and throws Matilde out of the hacienda. Soon after that, he starts a compromising relationship with Antonia that will later make his reconciliation with Matilde more difficult.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/television/20120716/1-recupera-misterio-venganza-pasion-amor-real/545694.shtml|title=La 1 recupera el misterio, la venganza y la pasi\u00f3n con 'Amor Real'|language=Spanish|work=[[RTVE]]|date=2012-07-16|accessdate=2012-07-22}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Main|List of Amor real characters}}\n* [[Adela Noriega]] as Matilde Pe\u00f1alver y Berist\u00e1in de Fuentes Guerra \n* [[Fernando Colunga]] as Manuel Fuentes Guerra\n* [[Mauricio Islas]] as Adolfo Sol\u00eds / Felipe Santamar\u00eda\n* [[Helena Rojo]] as Augusta Curiel de Pe\u00f1alver y Berist\u00e1in\n* [[Ernesto Laguardia]] as Humberto Pe\u00f1alver y Berist\u00e1in\n* [[Ana Mart\u00edn]] as Rosario Aranda\n* [[Chantal Andere]] as Antonia Morales\n* [[Mariana Levy]] as Josefina de Icaza\n* [[Ana Bertha Esp\u00edn]] as Prudencia Curiel\n* [[Beatriz Sheridan]] as Damiana\n* [[Mario Iv\u00e1n Mart\u00ednez]] as Renato Piquet\n* [[Mauricio Herrera]] as Urbano de las Casas\n* [[Oscar Bonfiglio (actor)|Oscar Bonfiglio]] as Sixto Valdez\n* [[Adalberto Parra]] as Delfino P\u00e9rez\n* [[H\u00e9ctor Saez (actor)|H\u00e9ctor Saez]] as Silvano Arzola\n* [[Kika Edgar]] as Catalina Heredia de Sol\u00eds\n* [[Ingrid Martz]] as Pilar Piquet de M\u00e1rquez\n\n== Production ==\n{{Quote box|width=25em|quote=\"The work of our extremely dedicated cast and crew, along with the extraordinary collection of visual elements \u2014 lighting, camera work, custom-made wardrobe, attention to detail \u2014 allows the viewers to experience the characters' emotions and also transport themselves completely to another era.\"|align=right|source=Carla Estrada<ref name=\"amorreal\"/>}}\n\n*''Amor Real'' is an adaptation of the telenovela, ''[[Bodas de odio]]'', from 1983, based on the novel of the same name, written by [[Caridad Bravo Adams]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sanchez|first=Claudia|url=http://celebra.aollatino.com/2010/09/15/telenovelas-literatura-herencia-hispana/|title=Telenovelas basadas en la literatura|publisher=[[AOL|Aol Latino]]|date=2010-09-15|accessdate=June 26, 2013|language= Spanish}}</ref>  For this version it was adapted by the Italian writer, Mar\u00eda Zarattini.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Salgado \n |first=Ivett \n |url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/impreso/8925418\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130629091912/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/impreso/8925418\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=2013-06-29\n |title=Antepone Mar\u00eda Zarattini la originalidad en sus historias \n |work=[[Milenio]] \n |date=2011-03-12\n |accessdate=June 26, 2013 \n |language=Spanish \n}}</ref>\n*The telenovela was filmed at the ex-[[hacienda]] of Tetlapayac and the surrounding area in the state of [[Hidalgo (Mexico)|Hidalgo]] for a lapse of eight months. Because the story takes place in mid-19th century [[Mexico]], sets of buildings and plazas had to be built.\n*The production, required the participation of over 1,000 actors, extras, technicians and artisans.<ref name=\"amorreal\"/>\n*[[Jorge Avenda\u00f1o L\u00fchrs]], Mexican pianist and composer, composed the original score ([[incidental music]]).\n*The opening theme, \"Amor Real\", was written and performed by the former Mexico-based duo, [[Sin Bandera]].\n\n==Reception==\n\n=== Mexico's television ratings ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Timeslot\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| # Ep.\n! colspan=2| Premiere\n! colspan=2| Finale\n! style=\"width:5%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Rank\n! style=\"width:7%;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:#ffdead;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Rating average\n|-\n! Date\n! span style=\"width:11%; font-size:smaller; line-height:100%;\"| Premiere<br />Rating\n! Date\n! span style=\"width:11%; font-size:smaller; line-height:100%;\"| Finale<br />Rating\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | <center>Mondays{{mdash}}Fridays<br>9:00pm</center>\n! 95\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>June 9, 2003</center>\n! 26.5<ref name=\"rating\">{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/123137/Amor+Real+alcanza+super+rating.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221150545/http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/123137/Amor+Real+alcanza+super+rating.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 21, 2014 |title=Amor Real alcanza s\u00faper rating |publisher=[[Terra Networks|Terra M\u00e9xico]] |accessdate=June 12, 2013 |language=Spanish }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cronica.com.mx/notas/2003/69310.html|title=Amor Real tuvo mayor rating a nivel nacional; Mirada de mujer, en el DF|work=[[La Cr\u00f3nica de Hoy]]|date=2003-06-11|accessdate=June 12, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| style=\"font-size:11px;line-height:110%\"|<center>October 17, 2003</center>\n! 43.1<ref name=\"rating\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://homozapping.com.mx/2011/12/telenovelas-en-2011-la-crisis-de-los-ratings/|title=Telenovelas en 2011, la Crisis de los Ratings|publisher=homozapping.com.mx|date=2011-12-28|accessdate=June 12, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n! #1<ref name=\"rating\"/>\n! style=\"font-size:smaller\"| 2003-04\n! style=\"background:#fc9;\"|29.4<ref name=\"audience\">{{cite web|url=http://i.esmas.com/documento/0/000/002/020/HistorialTln21Hrs.pdf|title=Audience history of primetime telenovelas in Mexico (1997-2007)|publisher=[[IBOPE]]|accessdate=June 12, 2013|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927130737/http://i.esmas.com/documento/0/000/002/020/HistorialTln21Hrs.pdf|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\nWhile on the air in Mexico, the telenovela registered very high ratings, especially in the final weeks of its airing when the telenovela showed an average of 35 points.<ref name=\"audience\"/> During the whole five-month run in Mexico, it remained on the #1 spot,<ref name=\"rating\"/> with a 60% market share, as reported by [[IBOPE|Ibope Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Morales|first=Magaly|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2003-10-29/lifestyle/0310280414_1_brazilian-tv-first-lesbian-kiss-telenovela|title=Brazil's First Televised Lesbian Kiss Brings Record Ratings For Globo|work=[[Sun Sentinel]]|date=October 29, 2003|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref> Due to the enormous popularity of ''Amor Real'', the entire telenovela was reruned for the second time after a public demand, only four months after the original airing finalized.<ref name=\"esmas\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.esmas.com/entretenimiento/biografias/009293/adela-noriega/|title=Datos biogr\u00e1ficos|publisher=[[esmas.com]]|accessdate=June 12, 2013|language= Spanish}}</ref>\n\n=== International success ===\nBesides the success in Mexico and Latin America, ''Amor Real'' was internationally successful, too.<ref name=\"amorreal\"/> When the telenovela aired during prime time on [[Univision]], it frequently managed to beat leading U.S. networks in the ratings.<ref name=\"wsj\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Cabot|first=Heather|url=http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/story?id=1508806|title=Romance! Revenge! Telenovelas Draw U.S. Viewers|work=[[ABC News]]|date=January 15, 2006|accessdate=June 15, 2013}}</ref> The series aired on Univision in the U.S. with no subtitles, however. It ranks among one of the Univision\u2019s highest rated telenovelas of all time.<ref name=\"upr\">{{cite web|url=http://corporate.univision.com/2013/press/univision-tlnovelas-network-premieres-epic-love-story-%E2%80%9Camor-real%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%93-one-of-the-most-successful-telenovelas-of-all-time/#axzz2YCZvFRT6 |title=Univision tlnovelas Network Premieres Epic Love Story \"Amor Real\" \u2013 One of the Most Successful Telenovelas of All Time |author=Univision.com |date=June 28, 2013 |accessdate=July 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221184616/http://corporate.univision.com/2013/press/univision-tlnovelas-network-premieres-epic-love-story-%E2%80%9Camor-real%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%93-one-of-the-most-successful-telenovelas-of-all-time/ |archivedate=February 21, 2014 }}</ref> The telenovela also had successful results when it aired in Spain, on the Spanish national television, [[Televisi\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola|TVE]], where it was shown in the afternoon, in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vertele.com/noticias/ultimo-capitulo-de-amor-real-en-la-tarde-de-la-primera/|title=\u00daltimo cap\u00edtulo de \"Amor real\" en la tarde de La Primera |publisher=vertele.com|language=Spanish|date=July 18, 2005|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvmasmagazine.com/news/tve1.php |title=El day time de TVE1 gana con Televisa |publisher=tvmasmagazine.com |language=Spanish |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110618015705/http://www.tvmasmagazine.com/news/tve1.php |archivedate=June 18, 2011 }}</ref> In 2005, ''Amor Real'' was released on [[DVD]] and it became the first telenovela to be released with English [[subtitles]].<ref name=\"wsj\"/> The DVD release had very successful sales in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Angelique|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/19078342/novelas-are-caliente|title=Novelas Are Caliente|publisher=ebscohost.com|date=November 2005|accessdate=June 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://azteca21.com/n/index.php/secciones/espectaculos/2692|title= La telenovela Amor Real rompe r\u00e9cords de venta en Estados Unidos en su versi\u00f3n DVD|publisher=azteca21.com|date=February 6, 2006|accessdate=June 16, 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref> The international DVD release of the telenovela, also included countries such as Canada, Puerto Rico, France, Italy and Spain.<ref name=\"dvd\">{{cite web|last=Tijerino |first=Carlos |url=http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/farandula/509066.html |title=El DVD de \u2018Amor Real\u2019 rompe r\u00e9cord |publisher=Esmas |date=February 3, 2006 |accessdate=June 16, 2013 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222152053/http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/farandula/509066.html |archivedate=February 22, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nHere are some of the nominations and wins for ''Amor Real'':\n\n{| class=\"sortable\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\"| 2003\n| rowspan=\"15\"| '''Gold Khalifa Awards'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/123075/# |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031119063746/http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/123075/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-11-19 |title=Arrasa 'Amor Real' con premios |language=Spanish |work=[[Terra Networks|Terra.com.mx]] |date=2007-04-09 |accessdate=2011-10-29 }}</ref>\n| Best Telenovela\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Leading Actress\n| [[Adela Noriega]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Leading Actor\n| [[Fernando Colunga]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best First Actress\n| [[Ana Mart\u00edn]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best First Actress\n| [[Beatriz Sheridan]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Female Antagonist\n| [[Chantal Andere]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Male Antagonist\n| [[Mauricio Islas]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| Ana Bertha Esp\u00edn\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actor\n| [[Ernesto Laguardia]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Co-Star Actress\n| [[Mariana Levy]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Co-Star Actor\n| [[Mario Iv\u00e1n Mart\u00ednez]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Co-Star Actor\n| [[Rafael Rojas]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Director\n| [[M\u00f3nica Miguel]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Direction of the Cameras\n| Alejandro Frutos\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| Best Television Script\n| Mar\u00eda Zarattini\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| '''Harlequin Award'''<ref name=\"estrada\"/>\n| Best Producer \n| [[Carla Estrada]]\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| '''The National Association of <br/> Broadcasters of Mexico AC'''<ref name=\"estrada\"/>\n| Golden Microphone Award \n| Carla Estrada\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| '''C\u00edrculo Nacional de Periodistas<br/> en M\u00e9xico'''<ref name=\"estrada\"/>\n| Palmas de Oro \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"background:#666699\"|<center>Won</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"39\"| 2004\n| rowspan=\"13\"| '''[[TVyNovelas Awards]]'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://img59.imageshack.us/img59/6304/pag2a.