Janet Leigh]] as Karen Weese\n* [[Hugh O'Brian]] as The Governor\n* [[Nancy Kelly]] as Alice Dakso\n* [[Johnny Seven (actor)|Johnny Seven]] as Detective Severino\n* [[Tamara Dobson]] as Lisa \n* [[Joseph Wiseman]] as Sam Druckman\n* [[Bruce Boxleitner]] as Cisco\n* [[Cooper Huckabee]] as Frank Gresham\n* Monica Gayle as Barbara Gresham\n* [[Lisa Hartman]] as Stewardess\n* Maggie Wellman as Kathy\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0076424|title=Murder at the World Series}}\n\n{{Andrew V. McLaglen}}\n{{Houston Astros}}\n\n[[Category:1977 films]]\n[[Category:1977 television films]]\n[[Category:1970s sports films]]\n[[Category:1970s thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Houston]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Houston]]\n[[Category:Houston Astros]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Andrew McLaglen]]\n[[Category:Thriller television films]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-thriller-film-stub}}\n{{sport-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_at_the_World_Series"}
{"title_page": "Maocai", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=April 2017}}\n{{Cuisine_of_China}}\n\n'''Maocai''' ({{zh|c=\u5192\u83dc|p=m\u00e0oc\u00e0i}}) is a stew-like dish originating from the [[China|Chinese]] city of [[Chengdu]], in [[Sichuan]]. It is composed of a variety of vegetables as well as meat and/or fish in a stock made of [[mala sauce]]. Although it is similar to styles of [[hot pot]] common in this region, its chief difference lies in the fact that the ingredients are already cooked when served, and hence no simmering is done at the table.\n[[File:\u4f20\u5947\u5192\u83dc 2.jpg|right|thumb|Maocai]]\n[[File:\u4f20\u5947\u5192\u83dc 1.jpg|right|thumb|Raw vegetables and meat to be selected at a maocai restaurant]]\n==Common Ingredients==\nAlthough there is great variation in the ingredients used in ''maocai'', typically any of the following vegetables are included: [[lotus root]], [[potato]] slices, [[Chinese cabbage]], [[cucumber]], [[winter melon]], [[cauliflower]], [[wood ear]], [[enokitake|enoki]], [[oyster mushrooms]], [[seaweed]], [[bamboo]] shoots, [[tofu]], [[tofu skin|yuba]], [[beansprouts]], as well as [[rice vermicelli]] and [[cellophane noodles]] made of [[sweet potato]] starch.\n\nThe meats most frequently encountered are [[beef]], [[pork]] and [[lamb and mutton|lamb]], although other meats and more specific cuts may be used too.\n\n==Preparation==\nThe name ''maocai'' is derived from the verb ''mao'' ({{zh|c=\u5192|p=m\u00e0o}}; [[Chengdu dialect]]: {{IPA|/mau\u02e8\u02e9\u02e7/}}) which in [[Sichuanese Mandarin]] refers to the blanching of the ingredients in a colander in hot water by moving the colander up and down repeatedly.<ref>{{cite web|title=mao cai - hotpot for one|url=http://dochengdu.com/post/107196124295/mao-cai-hotpot-for-one|website=DoChengdu.|accessdate=2 December 2016|ref=DoChengdu}}</ref> This pre-cooking of the ingredients before immersion in the stock sets it apart from most types of hot pot.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese cuisine]]\n\n\n{{China-cuisine-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:\u4f20\u5947\u5192\u83dc 2.jpg|thumb|Maocai]]\n[[File:\u4f20\u5947\u5192\u83dc 1.jpg|thumb|Raw vegetables and meat to be selected at a maocai restaurant]]\n{{Cuisine_of_China}}\n\n'''Maocai''' ({{zh|c=\u5192\u83dc|p=m\u00e0oc\u00e0i}}) is a stew-like dish originating from the [[China|Chinese]] city of [[Chengdu]], in [[Sichuan]]. It is composed of a variety of vegetables as well as meat and/or fish in a stock made of [[mala sauce]]. Although it is similar to styles of [[hot pot]] common in this region, its chief difference lies in the fact that the ingredients are already cooked when served, and hence no simmering is done at the table.\n\n==Common Ingredients==\nAlthough there is great variation in the ingredients used in ''maocai'', typically any of the following vegetables are included: [[lotus root]], [[potato]] slices, [[Chinese cabbage]], [[cucumber]], [[winter melon]], [[cauliflower]], [[wood ear]], [[enokitake|enoki]], [[oyster mushrooms]], [[seaweed]], [[bamboo]] shoots, [[tofu]], [[tofu skin|yuba]], [[beansprouts]], as well as [[rice vermicelli]] and [[cellophane noodles]] made of [[sweet potato]] starch.\n\nThe meats most frequently encountered are [[beef]], [[pork]] and [[lamb and mutton|lamb]], although other meats and more specific cuts may be used too.\n\n==Preparation==\nThe name ''maocai'' is derived from the verb ''mao'' ({{zh|c=\u5192|p=m\u00e0o}}; [[Chengdu dialect]]: {{IPA|/mau\u02e8\u02e9\u02e7/}}) which in [[Sichuanese Mandarin]] refers to the blanching of the ingredients in a colander in hot water by moving the colander up and down repeatedly.<ref>{{cite web|title=mao cai - hotpot for one|url=http://dochengdu.com/post/107196124295/mao-cai-hotpot-for-one|website=DoChengdu.|accessdate=2 December 2016|ref=DoChengdu}}</ref> This pre-cooking of the ingredients before immersion in the stock sets it apart from most types of hot pot.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese cuisine]]\n\n\n{{China-cuisine-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maocai"}
{"title_page": "Band III", "text_new": "{{RFbands}}\n'''Band III''' is the name of the range of [[radio frequency|radio frequencies]] within the [[very high frequency]] (VHF) part of the [[electromagnetic spectrum]] from 174 to 240 [[megahertz]] (MHz).  It is primarily used for [[radio]] and [[television]] broadcasting.  It is also called '''high-band VHF''', in contrast to Bands I and II.\n\n==Broadcast Television==\n\n===North America===\n\nThe band is subdivided into seven channels for television broadcasting, each occupying 6&nbsp;MHz.<ref>[http://www.csgnetwork.com/tvfreqtable.html TV Frequency Table] csgnetwork.com</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! Frequency Rangetryhjjvg5hikkk\n|-\n|7||174-180&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8||180-186&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9||186-192&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10||192-198&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11||198-204&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12||204-210&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13||210-216&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\n===Europe===\n\nEuropean Band III allocations vary from country to country, with channel widths of 7 or 8&nbsp;MHz. \n\nThe standard channel allocations for European countries that use [[Broadcast_television_systems#ITU standards|System B]] with 7&nbsp;MHz channel spacing are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! Frequency Range\n|-\n|E5||174-181&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E6||181-188&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E7||188-195&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E8||195-202&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E9||202-209&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E10||209-216&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E11||216-223&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E12||223-230&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\nThe [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] (8&nbsp;MHz) system is shown below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! Frequency Range\n|-\n|D||174-182&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E||182-190&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|F||190-198&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|G||198-206&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|H||206-214&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n<!-- \"i\" is usually rendered in lower case to avoid confusion with Band I channel 1-->\n|i||214-222&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|J||222-230&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\n=== Russia and other former members of [[International Radio and Television Organisation|OIRT]] ===\n\nRussian analog television is transmitted using [[Broadcast_television_systems#ITU standards|System D]] with 8 MHz channel bandwidth.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! Frequency Range\n|-\n|6||174-182&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7||182-190&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8||190-198&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9||198-206&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10||206-214&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n<!-- \"i\" is usually rendered in lower case to avoid confusion with Band I channel 1-->\n|11||214-222&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12||222-230&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\n==Radio==\n\nThe band came into use for radio broadcasting at the turn of the 21st century and is used for [[Digital audio broadcasting|Digital Audio Broadcasting]].\n\nIt is subdivided into a number of frequency blocks:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Block\n! Centre Frequency\n|-\n|5A||174.928&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|5B||176.640&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|5C||178.352&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|5D||180.064&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|6A||181.936&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|6B||183.648&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|6C||185.360&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|6D||187.072&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7A||188.928&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7B||190.640&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7C||192.352&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7D||194.064&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8A||195.936&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8B||197.648&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8C||199.360&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8D||201.072&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9A||202.928&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9B||204.640&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9C||206.352&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9D||208.064&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10A||209.936&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10B||211.648&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10C||213.360&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10D||215.072&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10N||210.096&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11A||216.928&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11B||218.640&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11C||220.352&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11D||222.064&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11N||217.088&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12A||223.936&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12B||225.648&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12C||227.360&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12D||229.072&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12N||224.096&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13A||230.784&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13B||232.496&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13C||234.208&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13D||235.776&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13E||237.488&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13F||239.200&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\n==Worldwide usage==\n\n===Europe===\n\nIn the UK and part of Ireland, Band III was originally used for [[monochrome]] [[405-line]] [[television]]; however, this was discontinued by the mid-1980s. Other European countries (including Ireland) continued to use Band III for analogue [[576i|625-line]] colour television.\n\nDigital television in the [[DVB-T]] standard can be used in conjunction with VHF Band III and is used as such in some places. The use of sub-band 2 and sub-band 3 band for [[Digital audio broadcasting|Digital Audio Broadcasting]] is now being widely adopted. Sub-band 1 is used for MPT-1327 trunked PMR radio, remote wireless microphones and PMSE links.\n\n===North America===\nIn North America, use of the band for television broadcasts is still widespread. Favorable propagation characteristics and reasonable power limits (up to 65&nbsp;[[kilowatt|kW]] for [[list of North American broadcast station classes|full-power]] [[digital television]], versus 20&nbsp;kW or less on [[VHF]] [[Band I]]) has meant that many US broadcasters elected to move their full-power [[ATSC]] stations from [[UHF]] frequencies to Band III [[VHF]] when all full-power [[NTSC]] [[analog television]] services in the US shut down in 2009.<ref>[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?state=&call=&arn=&city=&chan=&cha2=13&serv=DT&type=4&facid=&list=1&dist=&dlat2=&mlat2=&slat2=&dlon2=&mlon2=&slon2=&size=9 FCC TV Query: US DTV construction permit listings for VHF Band I (ch 2-6) and III (ch 7-13)]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{TVRband}}\n{{Audio broadcasting}}\n\n[[Category:Broadcast engineering]]\n[[Category:Radio spectrum]]\n", "text_old": "{{RFbands}}\n'''Band III''' is the name of the range of [[radio frequency|radio frequencies]] within the [[very high frequency]] (VHF) part of the [[electromagnetic spectrum]] from 174 to 240 [[megahertz]] (MHz).  It is primarily used for [[radio]] and [[television]] broadcasting.  It is also called '''high-band VHF''', in contrast to Bands I and II.\n\n==Broadcast Television==\n\n===North America===\n\nThe band is subdivided into seven channels for television broadcasting, each occupying 6&nbsp;MHz.<ref>[http://www.csgnetwork.com/tvfreqtable.html TV Frequency Table] csgnetwork.com</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! Frequency Range\n|-\n|7||174-180&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8||180-186&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9||186-192&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10||192-198&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11||198-204&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12||204-210&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13||210-216&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\n===Europe===\n\nEuropean Band III allocations vary from country to country, with channel widths of 7 or 8&nbsp;MHz. \n\nThe standard channel allocations for European countries that use [[Broadcast_television_systems#ITU standards|System B]] with 7&nbsp;MHz channel spacing are as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! Frequency Range\n|-\n|E5||174-181&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E6||181-188&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E7||188-195&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E8||195-202&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E9||202-209&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E10||209-216&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E11||216-223&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E12||223-230&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\nThe [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] (8&nbsp;MHz) system is shown below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! Frequency Range\n|-\n|D||174-182&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|E||182-190&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|F||190-198&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|G||198-206&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|H||206-214&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n<!-- \"i\" is usually rendered in lower case to avoid confusion with Band I channel 1-->\n|i||214-222&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|J||222-230&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\n=== Russia and other former members of [[International Radio and Television Organisation|OIRT]] ===\n\nRussian analog television is transmitted using [[Broadcast_television_systems#ITU standards|System D]] with 8 MHz channel bandwidth.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! Frequency Range\n|-\n|6||174-182&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7||182-190&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8||190-198&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9||198-206&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10||206-214&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n<!-- \"i\" is usually rendered in lower case to avoid confusion with Band I channel 1-->\n|11||214-222&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12||222-230&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\n==Radio==\n\nThe band came into use for radio broadcasting at the turn of the 21st century and is used for [[Digital audio broadcasting|Digital Audio Broadcasting]].\n\nIt is subdivided into a number of frequency blocks:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Block\n! Centre Frequency\n|-\n|5A||174.928&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|5B||176.640&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|5C||178.352&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|5D||180.064&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|6A||181.936&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|6B||183.648&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|6C||185.360&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|6D||187.072&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7A||188.928&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7B||190.640&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7C||192.352&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|7D||194.064&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8A||195.936&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8B||197.648&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8C||199.360&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|8D||201.072&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9A||202.928&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9B||204.640&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9C||206.352&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|9D||208.064&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10A||209.936&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10B||211.648&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10C||213.360&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10D||215.072&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|10N||210.096&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11A||216.928&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11B||218.640&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11C||220.352&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11D||222.064&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|11N||217.088&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12A||223.936&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12B||225.648&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12C||227.360&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12D||229.072&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|12N||224.096&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13A||230.784&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13B||232.496&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13C||234.208&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13D||235.776&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13E||237.488&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n|13F||239.200&nbsp;MHz\n|}\n\n==Worldwide usage==\n\n===Europe===\n\nIn the UK and part of Ireland, Band III was originally used for [[monochrome]] [[405-line]] [[television]]; however, this was discontinued by the mid-1980s. Other European countries (including Ireland) continued to use Band III for analogue [[576i|625-line]] colour television.\n\nDigital television in the [[DVB-T]] standard can be used in conjunction with VHF Band III and is used as such in some places. The use of sub-band 2 and sub-band 3 band for [[Digital audio broadcasting|Digital Audio Broadcasting]] is now being widely adopted. Sub-band 1 is used for MPT-1327 trunked PMR radio, remote wireless microphones and PMSE links.\n\n===North America===\nIn North America, use of the band for television broadcasts is still widespread. Favorable propagation characteristics and reasonable power limits (up to 65&nbsp;[[kilowatt|kW]] for [[list of North American broadcast station classes|full-power]] [[digital television]], versus 20&nbsp;kW or less on [[VHF]] [[Band I]]) has meant that many US broadcasters elected to move their full-power [[ATSC]] stations from [[UHF]] frequencies to Band III [[VHF]] when all full-power [[NTSC]] [[analog television]] services in the US shut down in 2009.<ref>[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?state=&call=&arn=&city=&chan=&cha2=13&serv=DT&type=4&facid=&list=1&dist=&dlat2=&mlat2=&slat2=&dlon2=&mlon2=&slon2=&size=9 FCC TV Query: US DTV construction permit listings for VHF Band I (ch 2-6) and III (ch 7-13)]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{TVRband}}\n{{Audio broadcasting}}\n\n[[Category:Broadcast engineering]]\n[[Category:Radio spectrum]]\n", "name_user": "2600:6c5a:657f:ea07:957d:52c4:22d7:b93f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNorth America)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Band_III"}
{"title_page": "Lake Kasumigaura", "text_new": "{{Infobox lake\n| name = Lake Kasumigaura <br> \u971e\u30f6\u6d66\n| image = \u3000Kasumigaura landsat.jpg\n| caption = The Landsat satellite picture of Lake Kasumigaura.\n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = \n| coords = {{coord|36|2|25|N|140|23|39|E|region:JP_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| type = warm [[Monomictic]]\n| inflow = Sakura and Naka rivers<br>and more than 30 small rivers\n| outflow = [[Tone River]]\n| catchment = {{convert|1,915|km2|abbr=on}}\n| basin_countries = [[Japan]]\n| length = \n| width = \n| area = {{convert|220|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = {{convert|4|m|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = {{convert|7|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume = {{convert|0.848|km3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}\n| residence_time = \n| shore = {{convert|252|km|abbr=on}}\n| elevation = {{convert|0.16|m|abbr=on}}\n| frozen = \n| islands = 0\n| pushpin_map = Japan\n| cities = [[Tsuchiura, Ibaraki]]<br>[[Kasumigaura, Ibaraki]]\n| reference = \n}}\n[[File:Lake Kasumigaura and Mt.Tsukuba,Inashiki-city,Japan.JPG|thumb|right|180px|The lake and Mt. Tsukuba viewed from the east]]\n{{nihongo|'''Lake Kasumigaura'''|\u971e\u30f6\u6d66|Kasumigaura}} is the [[list of lakes in Japan|second-largest]] lake in [[Japan]], located 60&nbsp;km to the north-east of [[Tokyo]].\n[[File:Ushibori in the Hitachi province.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Hokusai]]]]\nIn a narrower sense and officially, Lake Kasumigaura refers to a waterbody with an area of 167.63&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"gsi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gsi.go.jp/KOKUJYOHO/MENCHO/200810/kosyo.htm|script-title=ja:\u6e56\u6cbc\u9762\u7a4d|publisher=Geographical Survey Institute of Japan|date=2008-10-01|language=Japanese|accessdate=2013-09-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120804091311/http://www.gsi.go.jp/KOKUJYOHO/MENCHO/200810/kosyo.htm|archivedate=2012-08-04}}</ref><ref name=\"mlit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mlit.go.jp/river/toukei_chousa/kasen/jiten/toukei/birn30p.html|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u4e3b\u306a\u6e56\u6cbc|publisher=[[Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism]]|date=2002|language=Japanese|accessdate=2013-09-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912151833/http://www.mlit.go.jp/river/toukei_chousa/kasen/jiten/toukei/birn30p.html|archivedate=2013-09-12}}</ref> In a wider sense, Lake Kasumigaura can also refer to a group of contiguous [[lake]]s, which includes Lake Kasumigaura proper, hereby referred to as Nishiura (\u897f\u6d66), and two smaller lakes, Kitaura (\u5317\u6d66; 35.16&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup><ref name=\"gsi\" /><ref name=\"mlit\" />) and Sotonasakaura (\u5916\u6d6a\u9006\u6d66; 5.85&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup><ref name=\"gsi\" /><ref name=\"mlit\" />), and also encompasses the rivers connecting them. In this case the total area is 220&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.\n\nAbout 45% of the land surrounding the lake is natural landscape and 43.5% is agricultural land.\n\n== History ==\nLake Kasumigaura originally was a [[brackish-water]] [[lagoon]], with indirect connections to the Pacific Ocean via the Hitachigawa and Tone Rivers. In 1963, the construction of a gate near the confluence of these rivers disconnected the lake from its sources of ocean water. As a result, the salinity of Lake Kasumigaura declined, and today the lake contains fresh water. This lake was famous for its traditional fishery during the [[Edo period]]. But today, fishing production has drastically decreased due to [[water quality]] [[water pollution|deterioration]] that was partially caused by the closure of the tide gate in 1963 for purposes of desalination.<ref name=\"HavensOthert2001a\">Havens, K.E., P. Xie, T. Iwakuma, R.T. James, N. Takamura, T. Hanazato, and T. Yamamoto (2001). \"Nutrient dynamics and the [[eutrophication]] of shallow lakes Kasumigaura (Japan), [[East Lake (Wuhan)|Donghu]] (PR China), and [[Lake Okeechobee|Okeechobee]] (USA)\". ''Environmental Pollution''. 111(2):263\u2013272.</ref>\n\n== Use ==\nToday, Lake Kasumigaura is used for [[fishing]], [[irrigation]], [[tourism]], [[recreation]], and for [[Consumption (economics)|consumption]] by the surrounding public and local industry.\n\nA variety of fish can be caught from the waters of Lake Kasumigaura, including [[smelts|smelt]], Japanese [[Salangidae|icefish]], [[crucian carp]], [[goby]], [[Anguilla japonica|Japanese eel]] and [[freshwater prawn farm|river prawn]]. The most popular catch is cultivated carp, followed by smelt and goby. Another cultivated treasure from Lake Kasumigaura is the beautiful Kasumi freshwater [[pearl]]s. They were known for their high luster and rosy hues, which is the result of a four-year cultivation period. However, in 2006, cultivation was discontinued as cheap freshwater pearls from China proved too difficult to compete against.\n\nThe water from Lake Kasumigaura has long been used for the irrigation of [[paddy field]]s in the surrounding [[alluvial plain]] and upland fields on [[diluvium|diluvial terraces]] covered by thick deposits of [[volcanic ash]]. The primary crops are [[rice]] and [[lotus root]] (a local speciality). Other crops include [[tomato]], [[cucumber]], [[eggplant]], [[watermelon]], [[maize|corn]], [[edamame]], [[sweet potato]], [[kabocha]], [[daikon]] and [[peanut]].\n\nMany tourists come to the lake in the summer to view the \u2019\u2019hobikibune\u2019\u2019 (\u5e06\u5f15\u304d\u8239) [[sail]]ed [[fishing boat]]s which are unique to Lake Kasumigaura. The Suigo [[aquapark]], located in [[Tsuchiura, Ibaraki|Tsuchiura]], is popular during the hottest months. The [[windmill]] of Kasumigaura comprehensive park is a popular site along the shores throughout the year and especially in the spring when the [[tulip]]s are flowering.\n\nThe lake is a recreation hotspot. [[Sport fishing]] enthusiasts and [[angling|anglers]] can be found close to shore and around the river mouths surrounding the lake. [[Recreational boat]]s, such as [[yachts]], [[power boat]]s, [[sail boat]]s and [[personal watercraft]], are regularly enjoyed on warm weekends. The wide surrounding [[wetland]]s are wonderful for [[birdwatching]], as large numbers of [[water fowl]] can be observed, primarily during the wintering period. [[Japanese cormorant]], [[Bewick\u2019s swan]], [[little egret]], [[gray heron]], [[mallard]], [[European wigeon|Eurasian wigeon]], [[green heron]], [[sharp-tailed sandpiper]], [[bush warbler]], [[wood sandpiper]], Japanese [[marsh warbler]], Japanese [[reed bunting]], and the [[common coot|Eurasian coot]] are a few of the birds seen around the lake.\n\nLake Kasumigaura provides over 60 tons of water per second; most goes to agriculture (83%). The rest is provided to local industry (13%) and public (4%) in the [[prefectures of Japan|prefectures]] of [[Ibaraki prefecture|Ibaraki]], [[Chiba prefecture|Chiba]] and [[Tokyo]].\n\n== Challenges ==\n[[Eutrophication]] is a serious problem for Lake Kasumigaura. Legislation was enacted in 1982 to help prevent it, including a ban on the use and sale of phosphate-containing synthetic [[detergent]]s, and the control of nitrogen and phosphorus contents in the [[effluent]] from factories.\n\nIn order to help maintain the lake, dredging work is being carried out around the lake and at the estuaries of main inflowing rivers, such as Sakura River (\u685c\u5ddd).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Lake Kasumigaura}}\n* [http://www.city.kasumigaura.ibaraki.jp/hobiki/english/index.html Page on Hobikisen]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927205307/http://www.japanfs.org/en/public/ngo04.html Reviving nature around Lake Kasumigaura]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070715042829/http://www.ilec.or.jp/database/asi/asi-35.html Detailed information about the lake]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070901093417/http://www.pwri.go.jp/team/kasenseitai/eng/kenk2/html/206/lakekasumi.htm Data from the Public Works Research Institute]\n{{Lakes of Japan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Lakes of Japan}}\n[[Category:Lakes of Japan|Kasumigaura]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Ibaraki Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Lagoons of Japan|Kasumigaura]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox lake\n| name = Lake Kasumigaura <br> \u971e\u30f6\u6d66\n| image = \u3000Kasumigaura landsat.jpg\n| caption = The Landsat satellite picture of Lake Kasumigaura.\n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = \n| coords = {{coord|36|2|25|N|140|23|39|E|region:JP_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| type = warm [[Monomictic]]\n| inflow = Sakura and Naka rivers<br>and more than 30 small rivers\n| outflow = [[Tone River]]\n| catchment = {{convert|1,915|km2|abbr=on}}\n| basin_countries = [[Japan]]\n| length = \n| width = \n| area = {{convert|220|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = {{convert|4|m|abbr=on}}\n| max-depth = {{convert|7|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume = {{convert|0.848|km3|acre.ft|abbr=on}}\n| residence_time = \n| shore = {{convert|252|km|abbr=on}}\n| elevation = {{convert|0.16|m|abbr=on}}\n| frozen = \n| islands = 0\n| pushpin_map = Japan\n| cities = [[Tsuchiura, Ibaraki]]<br>[[Kasumigaura, Ibaraki]]\n| reference = \n}}\n[[File:Lake Kasumigaura and Mt.Tsukuba,Inashiki-city,Japan.JPG|thumb|right|180px|The lake and Mt. Tsukuba viewed from the east]]\n{{nihongo|'''Lake Kasumigaura'''|\u971e\u30f6\u6d66|Kasumigaura}} is the [[list of lakes in Japan|second-largest]] lake in [[Japan]], located 60&nbsp;km to the north-east of [[tokyo|T\u014dky\u014d]].\n[[File:Ushibori in the Hitachi province.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Hokusai]]]]\nIn a narrower sense and officially, Lake Kasumigaura refers to a waterbody with an area of 167.63&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"gsi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gsi.go.jp/KOKUJYOHO/MENCHO/200810/kosyo.htm|script-title=ja:\u6e56\u6cbc\u9762\u7a4d|publisher=Geographical Survey Institute of Japan|date=2008-10-01|language=Japanese|accessdate=2013-09-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120804091311/http://www.gsi.go.jp/KOKUJYOHO/MENCHO/200810/kosyo.htm|archivedate=2012-08-04}}</ref><ref name=\"mlit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mlit.go.jp/river/toukei_chousa/kasen/jiten/toukei/birn30p.html|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u4e3b\u306a\u6e56\u6cbc|publisher=[[Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism]]|date=2002|language=Japanese|accessdate=2013-09-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912151833/http://www.mlit.go.jp/river/toukei_chousa/kasen/jiten/toukei/birn30p.html|archivedate=2013-09-12}}</ref> In a wider sense, Lake Kasumigaura can also refer to a group of contiguous [[lake]]s, which includes Lake Kasumigaura proper, hereby referred to as Nishiura (\u897f\u6d66), and two smaller lakes, Kitaura (\u5317\u6d66; 35.16&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup><ref name=\"gsi\" /><ref name=\"mlit\" />) and Sotonasakaura (\u5916\u6d6a\u9006\u6d66; 5.85&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup><ref name=\"gsi\" /><ref name=\"mlit\" />), and also encompasses the rivers connecting them. In this case the total area is 220&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.\n\nAbout 45% of the land surrounding the lake is natural landscape and 43.5% is agricultural land.\n\n== History ==\nLake Kasumigaura originally was a [[brackish-water]] [[lagoon]], with indirect connections to the Pacific Ocean via the Hitachigawa and Tone Rivers. In 1963, the construction of a gate near the confluence of these rivers disconnected the lake from its sources of ocean water. As a result, the salinity of Lake Kasumigaura declined, and today the lake contains fresh water. This lake was famous for its traditional fishery during the [[Edo period]]. But today, fishing production has drastically decreased due to [[water quality]] [[water pollution|deterioration]] that was partially caused by the closure of the tide gate in 1963 for purposes of desalination.<ref name=\"HavensOthert2001a\">Havens, K.E., P. Xie, T. Iwakuma, R.T. James, N. Takamura, T. Hanazato, and T. Yamamoto (2001). \"Nutrient dynamics and the [[eutrophication]] of shallow lakes Kasumigaura (Japan), [[East Lake (Wuhan)|Donghu]] (PR China), and [[Lake Okeechobee|Okeechobee]] (USA)\". ''Environmental Pollution''. 111(2):263\u2013272.</ref>\n\n== Use ==\nToday, Lake Kasumigaura is used for [[fishing]], [[irrigation]], [[tourism]], [[recreation]], and for [[Consumption (economics)|consumption]] by the surrounding public and local industry.\n\nA variety of fish can be caught from the waters of Lake Kasumigaura, including [[smelts|smelt]], Japanese [[Salangidae|icefish]], [[crucian carp]], [[goby]], [[Anguilla japonica|Japanese eel]] and [[freshwater prawn farm|river prawn]]. The most popular catch is cultivated carp, followed by smelt and goby. Another cultivated treasure from Lake Kasumigaura is the beautiful Kasumi freshwater [[pearl]]s. They were known for their high luster and rosy hues, which is the result of a four-year cultivation period. However, in 2006, cultivation was discontinued as cheap freshwater pearls from China proved too difficult to compete against.\n\nThe water from Lake Kasumigaura has long been used for the irrigation of [[paddy field]]s in the surrounding [[alluvial plain]] and upland fields on [[diluvium|diluvial terraces]] covered by thick deposits of [[volcanic ash]]. The primary [[crops]] are [[rice]] and [[lotus root]] (a local speciality). Other crops include [[tomato]], [[cucumber]], [[eggplant]], [[watermelon]], [[maize|corn]], [[edamame]], [[sweet potato]], [[kabocha]], [[daikon]] and [[peanut]].\n\nMany tourists come to the lake in the summer to view the \u2019\u2019hobikibune\u2019\u2019 (\u5e06\u5f15\u304d\u8239) [[sail]]ed [[fishing boat]]s which are unique to Lake Kasumigaura. The Suigo [[aquapark]], located in [[Tsuchiura, Ibaraki|Tsuchiura city]], is popular during the hottest months. The [[windmill]] of Kasumigaura comprehensive park is a popular site along the shores throughout the year and especially in the spring when the [[tulip]]s are flowering.\n\nThe lake is a recreation hotspot. [[Sport fishing]] enthusiasts and [[angling|anglers]] can be found close to [[shore]] and around the [[river mouth]]s surrounding the lake. [[Recreational boat]]s, such as [[yachts]], [[power boat]]s, [[sail boat]]s and [[personal watercraft]], are regularly enjoyed on warm weekends. The wide surrounding [[wetland]]s are wonderful for [[birdwatching]], as large numbers of [[water fowl]] can be observed, primarily during the wintering period. [[Japanese cormorant]], [[Bewick\u2019s swan]], [[little egret]], [[gray heron]], [[mallard]], [[European wigeon|Eurasian wigeon]], [[green heron]], [[sharp-tailed sandpiper]], [[bush warbler]], [[wood sandpiper]], Japanese [[marsh warbler]], Japanese [[reed bunting]], and the [[common coot|Eurasian coot]] are a few of the birds seen around the lake.\n\nLake Kasumigaura provides over 60 tons of water per second; most goes to agriculture (83%). The rest is provided to local industry (13%) and public (4%) in the [[prefectures of Japan|prefectures]] of [[Ibaraki prefecture|Ibaraki]], [[Chiba prefecture|Chiba]] and [[Tokyo prefecture|T\u014dky\u014d]].\n\n== Challenges ==\n[[Eutrophication]] is a serious problem for Lake Kasumigaura. Legislation was enacted in 1982 to help prevent it, including a ban on the use and sale of phosphate-containing synthetic [[detergent]]s, and the control of nitrogen and phosphorus contents in the [[effluent]] from factories.\n\nIn order to help maintain the lake, dredging work is being carried out around the lake and at the estuaries of main inflowing rivers, such as Sakura River (\u685c\u5ddd).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Lake Kasumigaura}}\n* [http://www.city.kasumigaura.ibaraki.jp/hobiki/english/index.html Page on Hobikisen]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927205307/http://www.japanfs.org/en/public/ngo04.html Reviving nature around Lake Kasumigaura]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070715042829/http://www.ilec.or.jp/database/asi/asi-35.html Detailed information about the lake]\n* [https://web.archive