recipitation mm = 25.0\n|Apr precipitation mm = 34.0\n|May precipitation mm = 78.9\n|Jun precipitation mm = 248.5\n|Jul precipitation mm = 316.5\n|Aug precipitation mm = 310.0\n|Sep precipitation mm = 232.9\n|Oct precipitation mm = 73.7\n|Nov precipitation mm = 10.3\n|Dec precipitation mm = 8.2\n|year precipitation mm =\n|Jan rain days = 1.3\n|Feb rain days = 1.6\n|Mar rain days = 1.8\n|Apr rain days = 2.6\n|May rain days = 5.2\n|Jun rain days = 10.5\n|Jul rain days = 15.4\n|Aug rain days = 15.7\n|Sep rain days = 11.3\n|Oct rain days = 4.3\n|Nov rain days = 1.0\n|Dec rain days = 0.7\n|year rain days =\n|source=<ref>{{cite web|title=1981-2010 CLIM NORMALS (STATEWISE).pdf|url=http://imdpune.gov.in/library/public/1981-2010%20CLIM%20NORMALS%20%28STATWISE%29.pdf|publisher=[[India Meteorological Department]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205040301/http://imdpune.gov.in/library/public/1981-2010%20CLIM%20NORMALS%20%28STATWISE%29.pdf|archive-date=5 February 2020|access-date=26 March 2020|pages=399-400}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n{{Main|Economy of Jamshedpur}}\n[[File:Tata Steel at Night.jpg|thumb|Tata Steel at Night]]\nJamshedpur is home to the first private iron and steel company of India. The areas surrounding Jamshedpur are rich in minerals, including [[iron ore]], [[coal]], [[manganese]] [[bauxite]] and [[Lime (mineral)|lime]]. It is a modern, industrial city; the main industries being [[iron]] and [[steel]], truck manufacturing, tinplate production, cement and other small and medium scale industries revolving around these products.\n\nThe largest factory is that of [[Tata Steel]] (the erstwhile Tata Iron and Steel Company or TISCO), situated almost at the centre of the city. Tata Steel is the largest iron and steel producing plant in India, as well as the oldest.<ref name=Madan>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|url=https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= [https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada/page/179 179]|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref>\n\nTata Steel has been recognised as the best integrated steel plant twelve times; having won the PM's Trophy ten times and received the Certificate for Excellence twice.\n\nThe other major factory in the city is [[Tata Motors]] with Tata Hitachi Construction Machinery Co. Ltd, which manufactures heavy vehicles and construction/earth moving equipment. Tata Motors was previously called The Tata Engineering and Locomotive Company (TELCO), as railway locomotives were once manufactured here. The plant spreads over 822 acres, is one of the largest in the country, and at peak rate can roll out 450 vehicles per day.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1081106/jsp/jharkhand/story_10070363.jsp | location=Calcutta, India | work=The Telegraph | first=Ankush | last=Singh | title=Slowdown squeeze on Tatas \u2013 Five-day holiday to halt assembly of commercial vehicles | date=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nJamshedpur is home to TATA Cummins Private Limited (Formerly, TATA Cummins Limited), Tayo Rolls Limited (defunct),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/tata-steel-to-shut-down-arm-tayo-rolls/article24476474.ece|title=Tata Steel to shut down arm Tayo Rolls, sell SE Asia assets|last=Iyengar|first=Suresh P.|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> TRF, JUSCO and Tinplate Company of India Limited. Apart from the above large corporates, Jamshedpur has a varied and powerful industrial base established at Adityapur Industrial Area (managed by AIADA). Jugsalai is key market for wholesalers while Sakchi is popular retail low cost market.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{wide image|Jsrmetro1.jpg|500px|Jamshedpur City Skyline}}\nAccording to the 2011 [[census]] of India, the city of Jamshedpur had a population of 629,659,<ref name=\"2011 table 2\">{{cite web |title=Cities having population 1 lakh and above |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf |publisher=Census of India 2011 |accessdate=9 September 2019}}</ref> but the Jamshedpur Urban Agglomeration had a population of 1,337,131.<ref name=\"2011 table 3\">{{cite web |title=Urban Agglomerations/Cities having population 1 lakh and above |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf |publisher=Census of India 2011 |accessdate=9 September 2019}}</ref>  The city is designated as a Million Plus Urban Agglomeration as per Government terminology.<ref>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/1.%20Data%20Highlight.pdf</ref> Males constitute 52.1% of the population and females 47.9%. Tribals constitute around 28% of the population. Jamshedpur has an average literacy rate of 89.41% \u2013 higher than the national average of 74%. In Jamshedpur, 11.5% of the population is under six years of age.<ref name=\"censusindia.gov.in\">http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/india2/Million_Plus_UAs_Cities_2011.pdf</ref>\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions Jamshedpur City (2011)<ref name=\"JSRCITY\"/>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hinduism]]|orange|83.67}}\n{{bar percent|[[Islam]]|green|6.95}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikhism]]|pink|4.12}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christianity]]|blue|2.24}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism]]|yellow|0.16}}\n{{bar percent|[[Buddhism]]|grey|0.09}}\n{{bar percent|Others|black|2.67}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions\n}}\n\n{{see also|List of cities in Jharkhand}}\n\n==Civic administration==\n[[File:Jubilee Park, Jamshedpur.jpg|thumb|Jubilee Park, Jamshedpur]]\nThe civic administration of the city is under [[Greater Jamshedpur]] Metropolitan Region, Govt of Jharkhand.\n\nThe major urban local bodies are :\n[[File:Jsrmetro2.jpg|thumb|Jamshedpur Aerial View]]\n* Jamshedpur Industrial Town\n* Jamshedpur Notified Area Committee (JNAC)\n* [[Mango, Jamshedpur|Mango]] Municipal Corporation\n* [[Adityapur]] Municipal Corporation\n* [[Jugsalai]] Nagar Parishad\n* Kapali Nagar Parishad\n\n===Localities===\n{{See also|Greater Jamshedpur}}\n* [[Sakchi]]\n* [[Bistupur]]\n* [[Jugsalai]]\n* Northern Town\n* Telco\n* [[Sonari (Jamshedpur)|Sonari]]\n* Golmuri\n* Agrico\n* Tinplate\n* Sitaramdera<ref>http://tatanagar.com/localities-in-jamshedpur/</ref>\n* Nildih<ref>http://tatanagar.com/localities-in-jamshedpur/</ref>\n* [[Kadma]]\n* [[Adityapur]]\n*[[Parsudih]]\n*[[Birsanagar|Birsa Nagar]]\n*[[Mango (Jamshedpur)|Mango]]\n*Baridih \n*Dimna,Mango\n*Cable Town\n*Sidhgora\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Railways===\n[[File:Tatanagar Junction.jpg|thumb|Tatanagar Junction]]\n[[Tatanagar Railway Station|Tatanagar Junction]] is a railway junction and an A-1 category model station on the [[Chakradharpur railway station|Chakradharpur]]<nowiki/> division, of the [[South Eastern Railway Zone (India)|South Eastern Railway]]. Other railway stations in the city are Adityapur, Gamharia, Kandra, Govindpur etc.\n\n===Roadways===\n[[File:Mango Bus Stand (Jamshedpur Bus Terminals).jpg|thumb|Mango Bus Stand (Jamshedpur Bus Terminals)]]\n[[File:Expressway in Adityapur, Jamshedpur.jpg|thumb|Tata Kandra road in Adityapur, Jamshedpur]]\nJamshedpur is connected to other parts of India through national and state highways. The major highways are:\n* National Highway 33 (NH-33) touches the city and connects it to [[Mumbai]] and further joins the NH32, which connects with [[Kolkata]], [[Delhi]] NH-2, NH-33 and NH-6 connects it to [[Kharagpur]], [[Kolkata]].\n* National Highway 32 (NH-32) connects Jamshedpur to [[Dhanbad]], Via [[Bokaro district|Bokaro]].\n* Tata-Kandra Road connects Jamshedpur to Kandra via Gamahria.\n* [[Marine Drive, Jamshedpur]] connects Adityapur Toll Bridge to Mango via Kadma, Sonari through the western corridors of Jamshedpur\n\n=== Airport ===\n[[Sonari Airport]] is serving the city at present. It is spread over a 25-acre area in the Sonari area of the city. The airport is primarily used for bringing in chartered planes of TATA group.In previous days there were flights from jamshedpur to kolkata.\n\n[[Dhalbhumgarh Airport]] is a proposed public airport located at [[Dhalbhumgarh]], in the state of [[Jharkhand]], [[India]] as a Greenfield airport for Jamshedpur. It will be built on the site of an abandoned World War II airfield situated 60 kilometres from Jamshedpur on NH-33.\nThe old airfield was built around 1942, as an ancillary runway for other airfields in the vicinity that were being built around India's eastern frontier as part of the war effort. It was one of the airfields used by Allied forces to repel the advancing Japanese troops and to maintain transport links with China. As the Japanese forces came to control shipping in the China Sea, seaborne supply routes to China were cut and the difficult, 500&nbsp;km route over the Himalayas was increasingly used. The airfield was abandoned after the war.\n\nThe technical team of the [[Airports Authority of India]] (AAI) conducted survey in 2017 and approved the [[Dhalbhumgarh]] site for a greenfield airport. The government plans to invest Rs 300 crore through AAI for the new airport which will have a 3 kilometre long runway. In January 2018, Union Minister of State for Civil Aviation Jayant Sinha announced that the Union Civil Aviation Ministry and the Jharkhand Government would sign a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) for the construction of [[Dhalbhumgarh Airport]].\n\n==Education and research==\n{{see also|List of educational institutes in Jamshedpur}}\n\nImportant educational institutions in Jamshedpur are: [[XLRI]], founded in 1949; [[Mahatma Gandhi Memorial Medical College, Jamshedpur|Mahatma Gandhi Memorial Medical College]], established in 1961; and the engineering college [[National Institute of Technology, Jamshedpur]], an [[Institute of National Importance]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tatagrowthshop.com/sustainability/jamshedpur-glance.htm |title=Jamshedpur at a Glance |website=Tata Steel Growth Shop |accessdate=3 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aiada.in/web/advantage/training-facility.php |title=Training Facility |website=Adityapur Industrial Area Development Authority |accessdate=3 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Metallurgical Laboratory]] (NML), one of the 38 [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research]] (CSIR) laboratories, was inaugurated on 26 November 1950 by [[Jawaharlal Nehru]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nmlindia.org/60years.html |title=60 Years of Dedication to the Future |website=National Metallurgical Laboratory |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nShavak Nanavati Technical Institute (SNTI), established in 1921 as the technical training department of Tata Steel, now develops skilled employees for other companies as well. Its 400,000 volume library is one of the most popular in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://careers.tatasteelindia.com/working-with-us/learning-and-development.asp |title=Learning and Development |website=Careers at Tata Steel |accessdate=21 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110413204719/http://careers.tatasteelindia.com/working-with-us/learning-and-development.asp |archivedate=13 April 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sarkar |first=Soma Basu |date=31 January 2007 |title=Bookworms' paradise |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1070131/asp/jamshedpur/story_7329446.asp |location=Calcutta, India |newspaper=The Telegraph |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Tourist Attractions ==\n\n* [[Jubilee Park, Jamshedpur|Jubilee Park]]\n* [[Dalma Wildlife Sanctuary|Dalma Wild Life Sanctuary]]\n* [[Dimna Lake]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jamshedpur.nic.in/tourist-places/|title=Tourist Places {{!}} East Singhbhum|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n* [[Tata Steel Zoological Park]]\n* [[JRD Tata Sports Complex]]\n*[[Marine Drive, Jamshedpur]]\n*[[Dalma Hills]]\n*[[Ghatshila]]\n*[[ Beldih Lake]]\n\n==Sports==\n[[File:Official Jamshedpur FC Logo.png|thumb|125x125px|Official Jamshedpur FC Logo]]\n[[File:J.R.D. Tata Stadium.jpg|alt=|thumb|267x267px|J.R.D. Tata Stadium]]\nJamshedpur has a reputation as the sports capital of Jharkhand with Tata Steel promoting sporting activities. Jamshedpur's private clubs provide opportunities for activities, such as golf, tennis, squash, billiards, horseriding and water scootering.\n\n[[Jamshedpur FC]] is an [[Indian Super League|ISL]] team based in Jamshedpur. The team is owned by Tata Steel.<ref>http://www.indiansuperleague.com/jamshedpur-fc/</ref>\n\nAcademies and stadiums include:\n\n[[JRD Tata Sports Complex]] has an international standard multi-use stadium and an eight-lane monosynthetic track. It is primarily used for football and athletics but it has facilities for various other sports including archery, basketball, field hockey, swimming, table tennis, tennis, volleyball, skating, yoga as well as a modern gymnasium, are available at the complex. The stadium hosted the women football competition & archery event of the 34th National Games in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tripadvisor.in/Attraction_Review-g662321-d4138774-Reviews-JRD_TATA_Sports_Complex-Jamshedpur_East_Singhbhum_District_Jharkhand.html|title=JRD TATA Sports Complex (Jamshedpur, India): Top Tips Before You Go \u2013 TripAdvisor|website=www.tripadvisor.in|access-date=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Keenan Stadium]] hosted its 1st International One Day Cricket match on 7 December 1983 in which India lost to the touring West Indies Team. Many other International matches have been played here in which India has won only one match against South Africa in 1999\u20132000.\n[[File:Keenan Stadium aerial view.jpg|thumb|232x232px|Aerial view of Keenan Stadium]]\n[[Tata Football Academy]] was started in 1987 to nurture budding Indian footballers and raise the standard of Indian football. TFA is a football club in Jamshedpur, sponsored by Tata Steel. Today, Tata Football Academy is one of the premier [[association football|football]] breeding grounds in India.\n\nTata Archery Academy: archery is a sport indigenous to the tribal people of [[Chhotanagpur]] and Santhal Pargana. Tata Steel has pursued and nurtured the local tribals and provided them with facilities and training to bring them up to international competition standards in archery. Its students have attributed a lot of fame to the institute by bringing in many medals in National and International competitions.<ref>https://www.timesnownews.com/asian-games-2018-jakarta-palembang/article/deepika-kumari-profile-all-you-need-to-know-about-deepika-kumari-awards-records-ranking-india-s-medal-hopeful-in-archery-in-asian-games-2018/265264</ref>\n\nTata Steel Adventure Foundation \u2013 [[Bachendri Pal]], the first Indian woman to climb Mount Everest, is the director of Tata Steel Adventure Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tsafindia.org/index.php/profile/bpal|title= TATA Steel Adventure Foundation(Jamshedpur, India)}}</ref>\n\nJamshedpur has two golf courses\u2014the Beldih Golf Course and the Golmuri Golf Course. Both these courses are at the heart of the city. The biggest is the Beldih Golf Course which is around 6,000 yards. The Golmuri Golf Course although smaller is also challenging. They together hold the annual Tata Open Golf Tournament which is an event held under the support of the [[Professional Golf Tour of India]]. The tournament was started in 2002. Jamshedpur also has the Jamshedpur Gliding Club and the Jamshedpur Co-operative Flying club.<ref>https://www.avenuemail.in/jamshedpur/jamshedpur-flying-school-gets-approval-for-conducting-training-courses/120188/</ref><ref>http://www.tatagrowthshop.co.in/sustainability/jamshedpur-glance.htm</ref>\n{{wide image|Golmuri Golf Course.jpg|500px|Beldih Golf Course}}\n\n==Media==\n\n===Print media===\n[[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[English language|English]], [[Santali language|Santali]] and [[Bengali language|Bengali]] newspapers are published from the city, including ''[[Dainik Jagran]]'', Khobor kagoj<ref>https://khoborkagoj.com/</ref>  ''[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]'', ''[[Dainik Bhaskar]]'', ''[[Hindustan Dainik]]'', ''[[The Times of India]]'', ''[[Prabhat Khabar]], The Pioneer''{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} and ''The Avenue Mail''.<ref>{{Cite news |title=About us |url=http://www.avenuemail.in/about-us/ |work=[[The Avenue Mail]] |access-date=7 July 2017}}</ref> Jamshedpur Research Review<ref>http://www.jamshedpurresearchreview.com</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{see also|List of people from Jamshedpur}}\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order by LAST NAME \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n* [[Varun Aaron]], cricketer\n* [[Imtiaz Ali (director)|Imtiaz Ali]], director\n* [[Pratyusha Banerjee]], television actress\n* [[Priyanka Chopra]], [[Miss World 2000]] \n* [[Rasika Dugal]], actress\n* [[Gerald Durrell]], [[OBE]], conservationist\n* [[Ishita Dutta]], actress\n* [[Tanushree Dutta]], former [[Femina Miss India]] and actress\n* [[Ishank Jaggi]], cricketer\n* [[Saba Karim]], cricketer\n* [[R. Madhavan]], actor\n* [[Shomu Mukherjee]], filmmaker \n* [[Gourav Mukhi]], footballer\n* [[Shweta Prasad]], actress\n* [[K. V. P. Rao]], cricketer\n* [[Shilpa Rao]], singer\n* [[Randhir Singh (cricketer)|Randhir Singh]]<!--3 cricketers in Cricinfo, none from Jharkand-->, cricketer\n* [[Simone Singh]], Indian television actress\n* [[Saurabh Tiwary]], cricketer\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order by LAST NAME \u2666\u2666\u2666--->\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|India}}\n\n* [[List of tourist attractions in Jamshedpur]]\n* [[Economy and Industries of Jamshedpur]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Jamshedpur}}\n\n* [http://jamshedpur.nic.in/ East Singhbhum District Administration website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050306170527/http://www.tatasteel.com/corporatesustainability/jsr_glance.asp TataSteel.com: Fact File on Jamshedpur (Tata City)]\n* [http://www.galli.in/2012/09/welcome-to-tata-city-thomas-vanden-driessche.html Galli Magazine: Photo essay on Jamshedpur (Tatanagar / Tata City)]\n* [http://www.wikimapia.org/#y=22797547&x=86202850&z=13&l=0&m=s Wikimapia.org: Satellite images of Jamshedpur]\n\n{{Geographic location\n |Centre = Jamshedpur\n |North = [[Bihar]]\n |East = [[West Bengal]]\n |South = ''[[Odisha]]''\n |West = [[Uttar Pradesh]]<br />[[Chhattisgarh]]\n}}\n{{Kolhan Division}}\n{{Jharkhand}}\n{{Million-plus agglomerations in India}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Jamshedpur| ]]\n[[Category:1910s establishments in British India]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in India]]<!--year it was named Jamshedpur-->\n[[Category:All articles containing potentially dated statements]]\n[[Category:Articles containing potentially dated statements from 2011]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in East Singhbhum district]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Jharkhand]]<!--most populous, center of-->\n[[Category:Company towns in India]]\n[[Category:East Singhbhum district]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan cities in India]]\n[[Category:Planned cities in India]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1919]]<!--year it was named Jamshedpur-->\n[[Category:Tata Group]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia pages needing cleanup from August 2012]]\n[[Category:Populated places in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Jamshedpur\n| other_name                